    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just trying to \"gobble\" up some creative explanations, but I think I might have made a bit of a \"goblin\" mistake. There isn't actually a term like \"gobbling stress\" in horticulture, but I was trying to make a connection between the idea of pests or diseases consuming plant resources and the concept of stress.\n\nHowever, I think I might have inadvertently stumbled upon a real issue. \"Gobbling\" stress could be a colloquialism for a condition where plants are being over-eaten by pests, such as aphids or caterpillars, which can cause damage to the leaves and stems. This can lead to a weakening of the plant's defenses and make it more susceptible to other stressors.\n\nSo, while \"gobbling stress\" isn't a real term, it's possible that your tomato plants are experiencing some kind of pest-related stress that's causing the yellowing leaves. You might want to take a closer look at your plants and see if you can spot any signs of pests or diseases.",
